# Per-repo security pre-commit rules — additions to default.txt
#
# Format: SEVERITY|PATTERN|DESCRIPTION
#   SEVERITY = BLOCK (rejects commit) | WARN (prints warning, allows commit)
#   PATTERN  = extended-regex (passed to `grep -E`)
#
# Add rules specific to YOUR repo here. Examples below — tune for your project.

# ============================================================================
# Identity Isolation — names/emails/handles that shouldn't be in this repo
# ============================================================================
# WARN|alex.?wong|Founder real name (use generic example placeholders instead)
# BLOCK|alex@example\.com|Personal email address

# ============================================================================
# Brand isolation — for public skill repos that should be category-neutral
# ============================================================================
# Example: a public e-commerce skills repo shouldn't reference your specific
# competitors in templates / examples. Genericize them.
# WARN|brand_a|brand_b|brand_c|Specific competitor names — use generic placeholders

# ============================================================================
# Internal infrastructure (private repos that shouldn't leak hostnames if
# documentation/code is ever made public)
# ============================================================================
# BLOCK|api\.internal\.yourorg\.com|Internal API hostname
# BLOCK|212\.28\.182\.160|Internal VPS IP (rotate if leaked)

# ============================================================================
# Known-leaked credentials — remind on re-introduction
# ============================================================================
# After rotating a leaked credential, you can add the OLD value here as BLOCK
# so a stray re-paste from old code/notes triggers the hook.
# BLOCK|14a5bbed33ad1|Known-leaked proxy username (rotated 2026-MM-DD; never reintroduce)
